</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Companies sometimes issue convertible =
bonds. A convertible bond is a bond that can be converted into stock. Norma=
lly the conversion is at a fixed price that is above the price of the stock=
 when the convertible is issued.=C2=A0In 2014, Tesla Motors Inc. (now Tesla=
 Inc.) <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25723599.27=
0661/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEzMTg2MDUvMDAwMT=
E5MzEyNTE0MDc3Mjg4L2Q2Nzg2MTRkNDI0YjUuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa39ff22=
2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">sold $1.38 billion of 7-year convertible bonds</a> with a 1.25=
% coupon and a conversion price of $359.87, a 42.5% premium above its stock=
 price of $252.54 at the time. (At the same time, it sold another $920 mill=
ion of 5-year convertibles with a 0.25% coupon and the same 42.5% conversio=
n premium, though I will not discuss those bonds further here.[1]) When the=
 bonds matured seven years later (this March 1), Tesla=E2=80=99s stock was =
trading at $718.43. But in between Tesla had done a 5-for-1 stock split, ma=
king the effective conversion price of the bonds about $71.97. One $1,000 b=
ond converted at maturity=C2=A0into about $10,000 worth of stock. All the c=
onvertible bondholders converted by the time the bonds matured =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0some long before =E2=80=94=C2=A0and were happy and we will not=C2=A0talk=
 about them anymore.[2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When a company issu=
es a convertible bond, often it thinks: =E2=80=9CThis is fine, but I want a=
=C2=A0<em>higher=C2=A0</em>conversion premium. I don=E2=80=99t want people =
to be able to convert into my stock at 42.5% above my current stock price, =
because I think my stock will go up a lot. I want, like, a 100% conversion =
premium. I want to do a convertible that doesn=E2=80=99t dilute my stock un=
less my stock goes up a whole lot.=E2=80=9D But this is hard to do, in the =
convertible bond market; convertible-bond investors don=E2=80=99t want to b=
uy super-high-premium convertibles. So=C2=A0companies sometimes do=C2=A0wha=
t is called a =E2=80=9Ccall options overlay,=E2=80=9D or a =E2=80=9Ccall sp=
read,=E2=80=9D or a =E2=80=9Cbond hedge and warrant transaction,=E2=80=9D w=
ith their investment banks. In effect they buy an option from the banks (th=
e =E2=80=9Cbond hedge=E2=80=9D) that mirrors the conversion option in the c=
onvertible: In this case, Tesla=E2=80=99s $1.38 billion 7-year convertible =
would convert into about 3.8=C2=A0million shares of stock, so Tesla bought =
a 7-year option on 3.8=C2=A0million shares with a strike price of $359.87. =
(Those 3.8=C2=A0million shares automatically became 19 million shares after=
 the stock split.) And then they sell the banks a separate option (the =E2=
=80=9Cwarrant=E2=80=9D) at a higher strike price: In this case, Tesla sold =
the banks a 7ish-year warrant with a strike price of $560.6388, a 122% prem=
ium above the stock price when it issued the convertible bonds.[3] The over=
all result is that the company has effectively issued a synthetic high-prem=
ium convertible: If the stock goes up 80% or 100%, it will issue some share=
s on the convertible but get them back from the bond hedge; it only =E2=80=
=9Creally=E2=80=9D issues shares if the stock goes up more than 122% and th=
e warrant is in the money.[4]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Tesla=E2=
=80=99s banks owned warrants to buy Tesla stock. One of those banks was JPM=
organ Chase &amp; Co. Disclosure! Another one of those banks was Goldman Sa=
chs Group Inc. I used to work at Goldman Sachs, on the convertible bonds an=
d corporate equity derivatives desk, doing exactly these trades, though I w=
as long gone by the time of the Tesla deal (I left in 2011).</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">The banks, of course, hedge these warrants. Roughly speak=
ing the way you hedge a warrant is that=C2=A0you sell a portion of the unde=
rlying stock; as the stock goes up you sell more, and as it goes down you b=
uy some back.[5] The more often you do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0the more you buy=
